
1. Online Labs prerequisites (Ubuntu Lucid)

$ sudo apt-get install python-django
$ sudo apt-get install python-django-extensions
$ sudo apt-get install python-twisted
$ sudo apt-get install python-whoosh
$ sudo apt-get install python-simplejson

2. Installing Online Labs

$ mkdir online-lab
$ cd online-lab

$ git clone git://github.com/mattpap/femhub-online-lab.git
$ git clone git://github.com/mattpap/codenode-unr.git

$ cd codenode-unr
$ git branch --track femhub origin/femhub
$ git checkout femhub

$ bin/link-femhub `readlink -f ../femhub-online-lab/`

If /usr/bin/django-admin.py doesn't exist, issue:

$ sudo ln -s /usr/bin/django-admin /usr/bin/django-admin.py

To create a new environment (database, users etc.), issue:

$ cd devel
$ ./make-devel-env femhub-env

and say 'yes' when asked and setup admin's username, e-mail and password. This
way we created a new environment 'femhub-env'. The name can be arbitrary, but
it must be consistently used in the following section.

3. Running Online Labs

Now open two terminals in parallel and run the following commands:

$ ./backend-devel femhub-env
$ ./frontend-devel femhub-env

These will start two servers listening on localhost (8337, 8000).

Go to http://localhost:8000 and login. The site will redirect to
original Codenode interface at http://localhost:8000/bookshelf/.

Now go to 'settings' (top right corner) and redirect to 'Click
here for advanced settings' (only available for superusers). Go
to 'Backend servers' and click 'Add backend server'. Enter a name,
e.g. 'FEMhub', and address http://localhost:8337, and click save.

Redirect to http://localhost:8000/femhub. Now new Online Labs are
useble. Click 'New Notebook' to start work or 'Import' to import
a Sage notebook.

4. Importing Sage notebooks

Go to http://localhost:8000/femhub and click 'Import'. Copy plain
text from Sage notebook, e.g.:

{{{id=0|
some code
///
output
}}}

and click 'OK'. A new window will start with all cells imported.

